{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569227"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21969"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21969"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.08,0.02,0.02,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105795"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21969"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88264"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"11140"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"38828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41236"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105795"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of headache, blurred vision, and spontaneous gum bleeding. He also reports intermittent dizziness and mild confusion. He has a medical history of hypertension and is being investigated for unexplained weight loss and fatigue over the past three months. His regular medications are perindopril and amlodipine. He does not smoke or use alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 148/86 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. Fundoscopy reveals dilated, tortuous retinal veins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 110 g/L (130\u2013180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 7.2 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0\u201311.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 210 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150\u2013400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal protein 110 g/L (60\u201380)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum viscosity is elevated\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum protein electrophoresis demonstrates a monoclonal spike\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence high-dose corticosteroids","Begin allopurinol for tumour lysis prevention","Transfuse packed red blood cells","Start intravenous broad-spectrum antibiotics","Urgent plasmapheresis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of hyperviscosity syndrome, including headache, visual changes, mucosal bleeding, and neurological symptoms. The laboratory findings of elevated total protein and a monoclonal spike on serum protein electrophoresis suggest an underlying plasma cell dyscrasia. Hyperviscosity syndrome is most commonly associated with Waldenstr\u00f6m macroglobulinaemia, where IgM paraproteins cause significant increases in serum viscosity. While multiple myeloma can also cause hyperviscosity, this occurs less frequently and is usually associated with IgM, which is rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent plasmapheresis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. Plasmapheresis rapidly reduces serum viscosity by removing excess immunoglobulins from the circulation, providing prompt symptom relief and preventing further complications. It is the first-line therapy for symptomatic hyperviscosity syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence high-dose corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E may be part of the long-term management of certain haematological malignancies, but it does not provide immediate relief of hyperviscosity symptoms and is not the acute intervention of choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart intravenous broad-spectrum antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were signs of sepsis or infection, but there is no evidence of infection in this scenario. The patient\u0027s symptoms are explained by hyperviscosity rather than an infectious process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfusing packed red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E would increase blood viscosity further and could worsen the patient\u0027s symptoms. Blood transfusion is not indicated unless there is severe, symptomatic anaemia contributing to tissue hypoxia, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBegin allopurinol for tumour lysis prevention\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the acute management of hyperviscosity syndrome. Tumour lysis syndrome is a potential complication of cytotoxic therapy, but this patient has not yet started such treatment and is not at immediate risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyperviscosity syndrome is a medical emergency. Prompt recognition and treatment with plasmapheresis are essential to prevent irreversible end-organ damage. Definitive management of the underlying haematological malignancy should follow once the acute episode is controlled.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperviscosity syndrome most commonly occurs in Waldenstr\u00f6m macroglobulinaemia due to high levels of IgM paraprotein, though it can also occur in multiple myeloma.","Plasmapheresis is the first-line acute treatment for symptomatic hyperviscosity syndrome.","Clinical features include mucosal bleeding, visual disturbances, and neurological symptoms due to impaired microcirculation."],"references":["Perez Rogers A, Estes M. Hyperviscosity Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Mar 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518963/","Weaver A, Rubinstein S, Cornell RF. Hyperviscosity Syndrome in Paraprotein Secreting Conditions Including Waldenstrom Macroglobulinemia. Front Oncol. 2020 May 19;10:815. doi: 10.3389/fonc.2020.00815. PMID: 32509586; PMCID: PMC7248405. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32509586/","Gertz MA. Acute hyperviscosity: syndromes and management. Blood. 2018 Sep 27;132(13):1379-1385. doi: 10.1182/blood-2018-06-846816. Epub 2018 Aug 13. PMID: 30104220; PMCID: PMC6161773. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30104220/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88264"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21969"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88264"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-13T20:47:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-13T20:49:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14928"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105795"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c